message.content: This question requires knowledge about which organisms are capable of photosynthesis. Photosynthesis is the process by which plants, algae, and some bacteria convert sunlight into energy. Option (A) is incorrect because animals do not have the ability to perform photosynthesis. Option (B) is incorrect because people are not capable of photosynthesis. Option (C) is incorrect because water does not have the necessary structures and pigments to carry out photosynthesis. Option (D) is correct because shrubs are a type of plant and therefore have the ability to perform photosynthesis.

This question tests knowledge about which organisms are capable of performing photosynthesis. Photosynthesis is the process by which plants and some other organisms convert sunlight, carbon dioxide, and water into oxygen and glucose. Animals, including humans, do not have the necessary chlorophyll and other structures required for photosynthesis, so option (A) and (B) are incorrect. Water, option (C), is an essential component of photosynthesis, but it cannot perform photosynthesis on its own. Shrubs, option (D), are a type of plant and are capable of performing photosynthesis, making it the correct answer.

Animals (option A) and people (option B) cannot perform photosynthesis because they do not have chlorophyll or the necessary cellular structures. Water (option C) is not capable of performing photosynthesis because it lacks the necessary cellular structures and metabolic processes. Shrubs (option D), on the other hand, are plants and therefore have the ability to perform photosynthesis.
